data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already blocked synchronous LINQ by default but offered an opt-in (`AllowSynchronousIO`) to keep sync-over-async working. **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All your synchronous calls — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally because the underlying Cosmos SDK is async-only.

## The fix

Convert every sync call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (this ripples through controllers, services, etc.)
- Remove any `AllowSynchronousIO` or `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration — it no longer compiles.
